# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oak:unit-3701
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Global inequalities"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about global economic development. Pupils learn how, using a variety of measures, economic development is unequal and how this is reflected in demographic characteristics. Pupils learn about the causes and consequences of inequality and consider how they can be reduced."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit enables pupils to build on their global locational knowledge to consider patterns of economic development and inequality. Previously taught units on hazards help to inform an understanding of the causes of global inequality. Subsequent units build on this overview by considering resources, such as food, water and energy.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the terms 'economic development' and 'quality of life'
Pupils have global locational knowledge of continents and countries
Pupils can describe patterns and interpret maps, including choropleth maps
Pupils can identify and describe trends on graphs
Pupils understand the meaning of 'economic', 'social' and 'environmental'
Pupils understand the meaning of the term 'globalisation'
Pupils can assess different options and strategies to address an issue""" ;
  curric:id "3701"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.324191Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3704
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Jakarta: case study of a major city in an emerging country"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the development, importance and characteristics of Jakarta, an emerging country. Pupils will study the opportunities and challenges associated with the growth of the city, considering issues such as housing, services, the environment and sustainability."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of global urbanisation to develop a deeper understanding of the processes and patterns in an emerging city/NEE. They can contrast Jakarta with their earlier study of Liverpool. Knowledge gained can be used in the subsequent unit on energy resources.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a sound locational knowledge of the world and of Asia in particular
Pupils have an understanding of the geography of Indonesia
Pupils understand the terms 'social', 'economic' and 'environmental' in the context of cities
Pupils can describe and interpret maps, photos, diagrams and graphs
Pupils understand that city growth can create both opportunities and challenges
Pupils have an understanding of scale, in the context of national, regional and global
Pupils have an understanding of the factors leading to population change
Pupils understand the difference between 'top-down' and 'bottom-up' policies""" ;
  curric:id "3704"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.327451Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3697
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Global biomes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about ecosystems and biomes at different scales. Pupils learn about the factors influencing biome distribution and the physical systems and processes regulating them. Pupils will also learn about the impact of population growth and resource extraction on biomes."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of biomes and ecosystems developed in KS3 to develop a better understanding of the processes and factors influencing their distribution. Teaching the unit as this stage allows pupils to use the knowledge gained in subsequent units on the tropical rainforest and taiga biomes. It also allows pupils to use their knowledge as a context for filedwork studies later in the course.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Locational knowledge of continents.
An understanding of food chains and food webs.
Knowledge that nutrients cycle around ecosystems.
Knowledge of the meaning of an ecosystems and biome.""" ;
  curric:id "3697"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.327975Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3071
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Ecosystems, biomes and the biosphere"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about ecosystems and biomes at different scales. Pupils learn about the factors influencing biome distribution and the physical systems and processes regulating them. Pupils will also learn about the impact of population growth and resource extraction on biomes."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of biomes and ecosystems developed in KS3 to develop a better understanding of the processes and factors influencing their distribution. Teaching the unit as this stage allows pupils to use the knowledge gained in subsequent units on the tropical rainforest and hot desert/cold environments. It also allows pupils to use their knowledge as a context for filedwork studies later in the course.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Locational knowledge of continents.
An understanding of food chains and food webs.
Knowledge that nutrients cycle around ecosystems.
Knowledge of the meaning of an ecosystems and biome.""" ;
  curric:id "3071"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.328489Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3698
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Liverpool: changes in a UK city"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the geography of Liverpool, one of the UK's most important cities. Pupils learn about Liverpool's location and importance at different scales and about its characteristics. Pupils will learn about the factors leading to economic, social and environmental change."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their locational knowledge of cities in the UK and on the study of cities at KS3 to better their understanding of the factors and processes contributing to the characteristics and development of Liverpool. In subsequent units, pupils will be able to compare and contrast Liverpool with Jakarta, a city in an emerging country/NEE.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge about the UK
Pupils have an understanding of scale (local, national and global)
Pupils understand the process of migration, its causes and consequences
Pupils can describe and interpret maps and diagrams when assessing inequality and change
Pupils understand the terms social, economic and environmental
Pupils understand the meaning of sustainability
Pupils have an understanding of the key structure and functions of cities
Pupils know that cities interact with the surrounding rural area""" ;
  curric:id "3698"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.330100Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3298
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fieldwork"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about fieldwork, an important assessment component at GCSE. Pupils will learn about the six stages of enquiry (formulating a question; collecting, presenting and analysing data; and writing conclusions and an evaluation). Pupils will also consider four field study options."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Fieldwork is an essential part of geography and features as an assessment component at GCSE. This unit builds on the appropriate subject knowledge gained in earlier units and, at the start of Year 11, is an ideal time to embark on fieldwork (weather condusive to outdoor work, high level of pupil maturity, break in routine of study).""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have knowledge of basic fieldwork principles and practises
Pupils understand the importance of fieldwork
Pupils have knowledge of background subject content to enable meaningful fieldwork to take place
Pupils can work independently and collaboratively
Pupils have knowledge of techniques of data collection and presentation
Pupils understand the concept of risk assessment and can work safely in the field
Pupils have knowledge and competence in the use of IT, including GIS""" ;
  curric:id "3298"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.330759Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3699
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Fieldwork investigation"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about fieldwork, an important assessment component at GCSE. Pupils will learn about the six stages of enquiry (formulating a question; collecting, presenting and analysing data; and writing conclusions and an evaluation). Pupils will also consider four field study options."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Fieldwork is an essential part of geography and features as an assessment component at GCSE. This unit builds on the appropriate subject knowledge gained in earlier units and, at the start of Year 11, is an ideal time to embark on fieldwork (weather condusive to outdoor work, high level of pupil maturity, break in routine of study).""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have knowledge of basic fieldwork principles and practises
Pupils understand the importance of fieldwork
Pupils have knowledge of background subject content to enable meaningful fieldwork to take place
Pupils can work independently and collaboratively
Pupils have knowledge of techniques of data collection and presentation
Pupils understand the concept of risk assessment and can work safely in the field
Pupils have knowledge and competence in the use of IT, including GIS""" ;
  curric:id "3699"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.332525Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3703
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Urban change"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the causes and challenges of rapid urban growth. Pupils will learn about the trends and causes of urbanisationand will study how cities change over time."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their understanding of global inequalities and on their study of Indonesia to consider the global pattern of urbanisation. Pupils can use their knowledge gained in the subsequent unit on Jakarta.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have global locational knowledge of cities
Pupils understand the concept of urbanisation
Pupils can describe and interpret trends on graphs and maps
Pupils understand that cities exhibit distinct urban land uses
Pupils understand how economic development can affect the growth of cities""" ;
  curric:id "3703"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.336128Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3288
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Coastal landscapes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about coastal processes and landforms. Pupils will learn about the physical processes operating at the coast and about the formation of distinctive landforms of coastal erosion and deposition. Pupils will also learn about the importance and options of coastal management."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their previous knowledge of the UK's physical geography and geology by focusing on processes and landforms at the coast. Pupils can also make comparisons with river landscapes, studied in the previous unit. Knowledge from this unit will support the fieldwork unit.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a basic understanding of coastal processes and landforms from KS3
Pupils understand the principles of erosion, transportation and deposition
Pupils have an understanding of landscape
Pupils know the basic principles of how geology impacts on landscape
Pupils can use OS maps to describe, analyse and infer
Pupils can use aerial and ground photos in association with OS maps
Pupils have an understanding of the need for coastal management
Pupils understand the issues associated with flooding and why it is considered a hazard""" ;
  curric:id "3288"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.336725Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3296
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Indonesia: case study of a Newly Emerging Economy"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about Indonesia, a case study of an emerging country/NEE. Pupils learn about the location and importance of Indonesia at different scales and the economic and social characteristics of the country. Pupils will also learn about industrial developments, population and aid."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on and develop their understanding of global economic inequalities studied previously by focusing on Indonesia, an emerging country/NEE. They can also apply knowledge learned in the earlier study of Jakarta. Pupils can use knowledge gained in this unit when studying global resources later in the year.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of Indonesia and the wider world
Pupils understand the concept of economic development and of globalisation
Pupils can interpret maps, diagrams, graphs and photos
Pupils know and understand the different industrial/economic sectors
Pupils understand the characteristics of TNCs
Pupils know the meaning of international aid and its main sources
Pupils understand the meaning of 'quality of life'
Students understand the meaning and application of costs and benefits""" ;
  curric:id "3296"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.339607Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3292
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Places and people in the UK"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the human geography of the UK. Pupils learn about population distribution, the location of cities and the impacts of migration. Pupils also learn about the role of the UK government and the EU and the importance of globalisation in the UK's changing economy."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their previous locational knowledge of the UK from KS3 and begin to apply it to key economic themes, influenced by policies at home and abroad. This unit forms a solid foundation for further in-depth study of human geography in subsequent units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a locational knowledge of the UK, including regions and cities
Pupils understand the processes of migration and know the different types of migration
Pupils can describe patterns and analyse change on maps
Pupils understand the characteristics and values of cultural diversity
Pupils can understand the concept of globalisation
Pupils understand the meaning of primary, secondary and tertiary economic sectors
Pupils know and understand the characteristics and role of TNCs""" ;
  curric:id "3292"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.340127Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection .

oak:unit-3306
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Energy"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about different energy resources, their extraction and uses. Pupils learn about the different types of energy, the factors affecting extraction and the patterns and inequalites associated with production and consumption. Pupils also learn about energy futures."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their previous knowledge of global economic geography and the study of urbanisation to develop a better understanding of patterns and inequalities in global energy production and consumption. The placement of this unit towards the end of Year 11 reflects the high-level concepts that underpin this unit""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the difference between renewable and non-renewable energy
Pupils can describe patterns and interpret maps, diagrams and graphs
Pupils can use numerical and statistical skills to describe and interpret graphs
Pupils understand the physical and human factors affecting energy extraction/production.
Pupils have locational knowledge of the world's continents, regions and countries
Pupils understand the concept of ecological sensitivity
Pupils understand the principles of energy conservation and energy efficiency
Pupils understand the concept of sustainability in the context of energy resources.""" ;
  curric:id "3306"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.340661Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3303
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Global pattern of resources"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit, comprising of three variants, teaches pupils about global inequalities in food, water and energy production and consumption. Pupils learn about resource security and about sustainable futures."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit builds on the earlier unit which focuses on resources in the UK and enables pupils to develop a broader understanding of global inequalities in resource production and consumption. Having considered the global overview, pupils opt to study two resources in greater depth. This unit can support pupils in the subsequent unit on issue evaluation.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have global locational knowledge, of continents, regions and countries
Pupils have an understanding of resources and inequality of production and consumption
Pupils can describe and analyse patterns and trends on maps and graphs
Pupils can interpret choropleth maps
Pupils understand the concepts of resource security and sustainability
Pupils can understand why demand for resources is increasing
Pupils can demonstrate use of numbers and manipulate statistics""" ;
  curric:id "3303"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.342283Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3286
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Climate change"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the evidence, causes and impacts of climate change. Pupils learn that climate change is not just a recent trend but that it has occurred natuarlly over geological time. Pupils will also learn about the strategic options associated with mitigation and adaptation."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit naturally builds on pupils prior knowledge gained from studying weather hazards in the previous unit. Climate change underpins many of the issues considered in subsequent units, such as global economic development, energy resources and urban planning.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the difference between weather and climate
Pupils have a basic understanding of geological time
Pupils can describe and infer trends using maps, diagrams and graphs
Pupils can describe and infer trends using photos, including satellite images
Pupils can understand the difference between natural and human factors/causes
Pupils have locational knowledge of the world, including continents and oceans
Pupils understand that peoples' activities can lead to climate change""" ;
  curric:id "3286"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.412528Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3640
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Coastal, river and glacial landscapes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit, comprising of three variants, teaches pupils about processes and landforms associated with coastal, river and glacial landscapes. Pupils will learn about the formative processes involved in creating distinctive landforms and of the need for management."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their previous knowledge of the UK's physical geography and geology by focusing on physical processes and landforms in landscape development. Pupils may draw upon their knowledge gained in the subsequent unit on fieldwork.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a basic understanding of physical processes and landforms from KS3
Pupils understand the principles of erosion, transportation and deposition
Pupils have an understanding of landscape
Pupils know the basic principles of how geology impacts on landscape
Pupils can use OS maps to describe, analyse and infer
Pupils can use aerial and ground photos in association with OS maps
Pupils have an understanding of the need for management
Pupils understand the issues associated with physical landscapes, such as flooding""" ;
  curric:id "3640"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.414132Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3299
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Geographical skills"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about geographical skills. Pupils will learn how to identify, describe and analyse atlas and OS maps at different scales. They will also learn how to construct and interpret photos, diagrams, graphs and thematic maps. Pupils will also learn numerical and statistical skills."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils need to apply geographical skills throughout the course and this unit can be dipped into at any stage and as many times as necessary. This unit works well in association with the previous fieldwork unit as this is the most concentrated area of skills application in the GCSE course. In subsequent units, pupils can continue to practice their geographical skills.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand scale and direction on different maps
Pupils have experience of using atlas maps
Pupils have some experience of using OS maps at 1:50,000 and 1:25,000
Pupils understand the concepts of identification, description and analysis/interpretation
Pupils are competent in basic numerical and statistical skills
Pupils are familiar with ground, aerial (vertical and oblique) and satellite photos
Pupils understand the principles of GIS""" ;
  curric:id "3299"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.419280Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3696
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Climate change and weather hazards"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about climate change (causes, impacts and responses) together with extreme weather events, specifically tropical cyclones."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit naturally builds on pupils prior knowledge gained from studying weather and climate at KS3. Climate change underpins many of the issues considered in subsequent units, such as global economic development, energy resources and urban planning.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the difference between weather and climate
Pupils have a basic understanding of geological time
Pupils can describe and infer trends using maps, diagrams and graphs
Pupils can describe and infer trends using photos, including satellite images
Pupils can understand the difference between natural and human factors/causes
Pupils have locational knowledge of the world, including continents and oceans
Pupils understand that peoples' activities can lead to climate change""" ;
  curric:id "3696"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.421980Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3264
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Hot desert and cold environments"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the location, characterisitics, opprtunities and challenges associated with one global environment, either hot deserts or cold environments. Pupils will also learn about plant and animal adaptation and about issues facing their chosen environment."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of small-scale ecosystems and large-scale biomes to develop a comprehensive understanding of a chosen extreme environment, either a hot desert or a cold environment. Understanding the connections between physical and human processes will provide a foundation in studying subsequent units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have global locational knowledge and can use atlas maps
Pupils understand that plants and animals adapt to their environment
Pupils understand the terms 'biotic' and 'abiotic' in the context of ecosystems
Pupils can describe and infer using photos
Pupils understand the concept of interdependence and the importance of biodiversity
Pupils know that people living in extreme environments face challenges and opportunities""" ;
  curric:id "3264"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.460270Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3300
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Patterns of global urbanisation"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about patterns and trends in global urbanisation. Pupils study regional variations, patterns and growth in urbanisation and the development of megacities. Pupils also learn about the changing factors affecting growth, urban land uses and sustainable urban living."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of global urban geography from KS3  to develop a greater depth of understanding of the processes and consequences of urbanisation. This unit sets the scene and provides an appropriate context for the more detailed city case study (Jakarta) in the next unit.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the meaning of 'urbanisation' in a global context
Pupils know about the main causes of urban growth
Pupils have locational knowledge of continents and global regions
Pupils can describe patterns and trends using maps and graphs
Pupils have an understanding of the factors affecting migration and natural change
Pupils understand the meaning of developed, emerging and developing countries
Pupils understand the meaning of 'sustainability' in the context of urban environments""" ;
  curric:id "3300"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.461279Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3297
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Economic futures in the UK"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches economic change in the UK. Pupils will learn about the causes of economic change and the move to a post-industrial economy. Pupils will learn about economic developments in rural areas, developments in transport, the north-south divide and the role of the UK in the wider world."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their prior knowledge of economic geography and use their understanding of key terms such as globalisation learned in previous units to focus and better understand economic change in the UK. Some pupils can go on to use their knowledge gained in this unit for their fieldwork later in the course.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of the geography of the UK
Pupils understand the meaning of 'economic' together with key terms such as 'globalisation'
Pupils can describe trends and patterns associated with change on maps, diagrams and graphs
Pupils can understand the social and economic  implications of population change
Pupils understand the term 'infrastructure' in the context of transport
Pupils have global locational knowledge of continents, regions and countries""" ;
  curric:id "3297"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.461792Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3694
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Geographical and statistics skills"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about geographical skills. Pupils will learn how to identify, describe and analyse atlas and OS maps at different scales. They will also learn how to construct and interpret photos, diagrams, graphs and thematic maps. Pupils will also learn numerical and statistical skills."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils need to apply geographical skills throughout the course and this unit can be dipped into at any stage and as many times as necessary. This unit works well in association with the previous fieldwork unit as this is the most concentrated area of skills application in the GCSE course. In subsequent units, pupils can continue to practice their geographical skills.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand scale and direction on different maps
Pupils have experience of using atlas maps
Pupils have some experience of using OS maps at 1:50,000 and 1:25,000
Pupils understand the concepts of identification, description and analysis/interpretation
Pupils are competent in basic numerical and statistical skills
Pupils are familiar with ground, aerial (vertical and oblique) and satellite photos
Pupils understand the principles of GIS""" ;
  curric:id "3694"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.467195Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3301
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Jakarta: case study of a major city in a Newly Emerging Economy"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the development, importance and characteristics of Jakarta, an emerging country/NEE. Pupils will study the opportunities and challenges associated with the growth of the city, considering issues such as housing, services, the environment and sustainability."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of global urbanisation from the previous unit to develop a deeper understanding of the processes and patterns in an emerging city/NEE. In the subsequent unit, pupils can contrast Jakarta with the city of Liverpool.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a sound locational knowledge of the world and of Asia in particular
Pupils have an understanding of the geography of Indonesia
Pupils understand the terms 'social', 'economic' and 'environmental' in the context of cities
Pupils can describe and interpret maps, photos, diagrams and graphs
Pupils understand that city growth can create both opportunities and challenges
Pupils have an understanding of scale, in the context of national, regional and global
Pupils have an understanding of the factors leading to population change
Pupils understand the difference between 'top-down' and 'bottom-up' policies""" ;
  curric:id "3301"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.468194Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3284
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Natural and tectonic hazards"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about natural and tectonic hazards, their location, causes and effects. Pupils learn about the different types of hazard before focusing on earthquakes and volcanoes. Pupils will learn about tectonic processes, hazard impacts and the options for mitigation and adaptation."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of earthquakes and volcanoes studied at KS3, and on their global locational knowledge to develop a more in-depth understanding of natural hazards. Having studied physical systems and processes at the global scale, pupils can go on to learn about smaller-scale landscape processes, such as rivers and coasts.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have global locational knowledge and can use atlas maps
Pupils will be able to describe and interpret patterns on maps and graphs
Pupils understand the concept of 'hazards' as applied to the physical world
Pupils have an understanding of geological time in the context of tectonic processes
Pupils understand that hazards can have primary and secondary impacts
Pupils understand the difference between short-term and long-term responses to hazards
Pupils can describe, interpret and infer using photos
Pupils understand the role of development (HIC/LIC) on hazard impacts and responses
Pupils understand that management ca reduce the impacts of hazards""" ;
  curric:id "3284"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.471990Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3295
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Global variations in economic development"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about global economic development. Pupils learn how, using a variety of measures, economic development is unequal and how this is reflected in demographic characteristics. Pupils learn about the causes and consequences of inequality and consider how they can be reduced."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit enables pupils to build on their global locational knowledge to consider patterns of economic development and inequality. Previously taught units on hazards help to inform an understanding of the causes of global inequality. Subsequent units build on this overview by considering resources, such as food, water and energy.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the terms 'economic development' and 'quality of life'
Pupils have global locational knowledge of continents and countries
Pupils can describe patterns and interpret maps, including choropleth maps
Pupils can identify and describe trends on graphs
Pupils understand the meaning of 'economic', 'social' and 'environmental'
Pupils understand the meaning of the term 'globalisation'
Pupils can assess different options and strategies to address an issue""" ;
  curric:id "3295"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.544877Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3302
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Resources in the UK"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about natural resources in the UK. Pupils will learn about the demand and provision of food, water and energy in the UK and the associated opportunities and challenges."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their prior knowledge of the human geography of the UK to develop an understanding of the country's resources, food, water and energy. The subsequent unit develops the study of resources by considering issues and inequalities at the global scale.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of the UK
Pupils understand the term 'resource' in the context of food, water and energy
Pupils understand the concepts of opportunities and challenges
Pupils have an understanding of the carbon footprint and the factors that affect it
Pupils can identify, describe and analyse trends and patterns on maps and graphs
Pupils know the principles of supply and demand
Pupils understand the term 'energy mix'""" ;
  curric:id "3302"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.546007Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3702
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Indonesia: case study of an emerging country"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about Indonesia, a case study of an emerging country. Pupils learn about the location and importance of Indonesia at different scales and the economic and social characteristics of the country. Pupils will also learn about industrial developments, population and aid."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on and develop their understanding of global economic inequalities studied previously by focusing on Indonesia, an emerging country. They can further their understanding of industrial sectors (studied in KS3) and globalisation. Subsequently, pupils will use this knowledge when studying Jakarta later in the course.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of Indonesia and the wider world
Pupils understand the concept of economic development and of globalisation
Pupils can interpret maps, diagrams, graphs and photos
Pupils know and understand the different industrial/economic sectors
Pupils understand the characteristics of TNCs
Pupils know the meaning of international aid and its main sources
Pupils understand the meaning of 'quality of life'
Students understand the meaning and application of costs and benefits""" ;
  curric:id "3702"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.546918Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3705
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Making geographical decisions"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils how to address a key exam component, 'Making a Decision'. Pupils learn how to address these important geographical skills to support them in the run-up to the exam."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This final unit is based on selected geographical content studied during Years 10 and 11. Pupils need the knowledge and skills learned throughout the course to enable them to achieve success Making a Decision.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the assessment structure and the weighting of this component
Pupils know the importance of writing a balanced answer, considering different people's views
Pupils have an understanding of the process of decision-making in geography
Pupils can make a decision and use supporting evidence to back it up
Pupils have experience of debating and making judgements""" ;
  curric:id "3705"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.552309Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection .

oak:unit-3307
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Decision making in geography"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils how to address a key exam component, Issue Evaluation. Pupils learn how to address these important geographical skills to support them in the run-up to the exam."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """This final unit is based on selected geographical content studied during Years 10 and 11. Pupils need the knowledge and skills learned throughout the course to enable them to achieve success in Issue Evaluation.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils understand the assessment structure and the weighting of this component
Pupils know the importance of writing a balanced answer, considering different people's views
Pupils have an understanding of the process of decision-making in geography
Pupils can make a decision and use supporting evidence to back it up
Pupils have experience of debating and making judgements""" ;
  curric:id "3307"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.552811Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection .

oak:unit-3073
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Tropical rainforest and taiga biomes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about tropical rainforest and taiga biomes. Pupils learn about its biotic and abiotic characteristics, the adaptations of plants and animals and the threats facing its biodiversity. The unit considers opposing views on protecting and exploiting resources."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of ecosystems and biomes developed in earlier lessons to develop an understanding of the characteristics and threats facing tropical rainforest and taiga biomes. Pupils will be able to apply their knowledge in subsequent units focusing on global development and resource management.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have an understanding of ecosystems and biomes
Pupils know the difference between biotic (living) and abiotic (non-living) factors
Pupils have knowledge and understanding of the nutrient cycle
Pupils can interpret graphs and maps showing change
Pupils understand the threats to forest biomes
Pupils have an understanding of the concept of wilderness
Pupils can appreciate that different groups of people can have opposing views""" ;
  curric:id "3073"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.607869Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3072
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Tropical rainforest"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the tropical rainforest biome. Pupils learn about  the biotic and abiotic characteristics of tropical rainforests and the adaptations of plants and animals. Pupils will also learn about the importance of tropical rainforests and how they are under threat."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of ecosystems and biomes to develop their understanding of the tropical rainforest biome, its distribution, characteristics and threats. This unit builds on the knowledge gained earlier and enables comparisons to be made when studying future units on hot desert and cold environments.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils can demonstrate locational knowledge of continents
Pupils have an understanding of ecosystems and biomes
Pupils have an understanding of the climatic factors affecting biomes
Pupils know the difference between biotic (living) and abiotic (non-living) factors
Pupils have knowledge and understanding of the nutrient cycle
Pupils can interpret graphs and maps showing rates of change
Pupils can understand the importance of scale""" ;
  curric:id "3072"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.675393Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3293
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Liverpool: case study of a UK city"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the geography of Liverpool, one of the UK's most important cities. Pupils learn about Liverpool's location and importance at different scales and about its characteristics. Pupils will learn about the factors leading to economic, social and environmental change."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their locational knowledge of cities in the UK and on the study of Jakarta in the previous unit to better their understanding of the factors and processes contributing to the characteristics and development of Liverpool. In subsequent units, pupils will be able to apply their knowledge in studying economic geography and resources.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge about the UK
Pupils have an understanding of scale (local, national and global)
Pupils understand the process of migration, its causes and consequences
Pupils can describe and interpret maps and diagrams when assessing inequality and change
Pupils understand the terms social, economic and environmental
Pupils understand the meaning of sustainability
Pupils have an understanding of the key structure and functions of cities
Pupils know that cities interact with the surrounding rural area""" ;
  curric:id "3293"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.675914Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-inequality ,
    oak:thread-globalisation-and-interconnection ,
    oak:thread-human-systems-and-processes ,
    oak:thread-representation-and-identity .

oak:unit-3287
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The UK's physical landscape"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """THis unit teaches pupils about the UK's physical landscape, forming a solid foundation for further studies of physical systems and processes. Pupils learn how geology and past processes have influenced the physical and human landscape of the UK."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their existing knowledge of of the UK to gain - through the study of geology - a more in-depth understanding of the UK's distinctive landscapes. This unit provides an important context for future units focusing on physical processes and landforms.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of the UK
Pupils understand geology and have an appreciation of geological time
Pupils know the terms 'igneous', 'sedimentary' and 'metamorphic'
Pupils have some knowledge of major UK rock types, ideally from examining specimens
Pupils can describe (geological) patterns on maps
Pupils understand that physical and human processes interact to create landscapes""" ;
  curric:id "3287"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.676404Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3285
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Weather hazards"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about weather hazards at the global and national (UK) scales. Pupils learn about global atmospheric circulation before focusing on the formation, impacts and responses to tropical storms. Pupils also learn about extreme weather events in the UK."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of weather and climate developed in KS3 to consider the global context before focusing on tropical cyclones. Teaching the unit at this stage enables pupils to apply knowledge of hazards learned earlier in the year to the weather. It also allows pupils to use their knowledge of weather hazards when addressing development issues in subsequent units.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of the world - continents, regions and countries
Pupils know the difference between weather and climate
Pupils understand the concept of circulation
Pupils can interpret evidence on maps, diagrams and photos, including satellite images
Pupils understand the concept of hazards, including primary and secondary impacts
Pupils understand the difference between short-term and long-term responses
Pupils have locational knowledge of the UK
Pupils can describe change using graphs and extrapolate into the future""" ;
  curric:id "3285"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.681502Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-sustainability-and-climate-change ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3289
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "River landscapes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about river processes and landforms. Pupils will learn about the physical processes operating in rivers and about the formation of distinctive landforms of river erosion and deposition. Pupils will also learn about the importance and options of river management."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their previous knowledge of the UK's physical geography  by studying river processes and landforms. Teaching this unit provides pupils with a template to studying physical environments by considering processes, landforms and management. This enables comparison to be made with coasts in the next unit. Knowledge gained will also support the fieldwork unit.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have a basic understanding of river processes and landforms from KS3
Pupils understand the principles of erosion, transportation and deposition
Pupils have an understanding of landscape
Pupils can use OS maps to describe, analyse and infer
Pupils can use aerial and ground photos in association with OS maps
Pupils are familiar with and can interpret cross sections
Pupils can draw and interpret a line graph, using values on two axes
Pupils have an understanding of the need for river management
Pupils understand the issues associated with flooding and why it is considered a hazard""" ;
  curric:id "3289"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.689891Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3695
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Tectonic hazards"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about tectonic hazards, their location, causes and effects. Pupils learn about the different types of hazard before focusing on earthquakes and volcanoes. Pupils will learn about tectonic processes, hazard impacts and the options for mitigation and adaptation."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their knowledge of earthquakes and volcanoes studied at KS3, and on their global locational knowledge to develop a more in-depth understanding of natural hazards. Having studied physical systems and processes at the global scale, pupils can go on to learn about smaller-scale landscape processes, such as rivers and coasts.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have global locational knowledge and can use atlas maps
Pupils will be able to describe and interpret patterns on maps and graphs
Pupils understand the concept of 'hazards' as applied to the physical world
Pupils have an understanding of geological time in the context of tectonic processes
Pupils understand that hazards can have primary and secondary impacts
Pupils understand the difference between short-term and long-term responses to hazards
Pupils can describe, interpret and infer using photos
Pupils understand the role of development (HIC/LIC) on hazard impacts and responses
Pupils understand that management ca reduce the impacts of hazards""" ;
  curric:id "3695"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.720042Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-risk-and-resilience ,
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

oak:unit-3700
  a oakcurric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "UK physical landscapes"@en ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit teaches pupils about the UK's physical landscape, forming a solid foundation for further studies of physical systems and processes. Pupils learn how geology and past processes have influenced the physical and human landscape of the UK."""@en ;
  oakcurric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils can build on their existing knowledge of of the UK to gain - through the study of geology - a more in-depth understanding of the UK's distinctive landscapes. This unit provides an important context for future units focusing on physical processes and landforms.""" ;
  oakcurric:unitPriorKnowledgeRequirements """Pupils have locational knowledge of the UK
Pupils understand geology and have an appreciation of geological time
Pupils know the terms 'igneous', 'sedimentary' and 'metamorphic'
Pupils have some knowledge of major UK rock types, ideally from examining specimens
Pupils can describe (geological) patterns on maps
Pupils understand that physical and human processes interact to create landscapes""" ;
  curric:id "3700"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:07.727670Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  oakcurric:isUnitOf oak:scheme-geography-key-stage-4 ;
  oakcurric:includesThread
    oak:thread-physical-systems-and-processes .

